At this point, in both pieces‚ a person enters who speaks words of comfort. The following parallel establishes the relation between Webster's scene and the story in the Arcadia :—

“It happened, at that time upon his bed, toward the dawning of the day, he heard one stir in his chamber, by the motion of garments, and with an angry voice asked who was there. ‘A poor gentle- woman,' answered the party, ‘that wish[es] long life unto you.' ‘And 1 soon death unto you,’ said he, ‘for the horrible curse you have given me.’”—“Arcadia,” book iii.
